observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the management agreed that:

a.	The Inventory Committee prepare and submit the CY 2023 RPCPPE immediately, and henceforth ensure the timely preparation and submission of the annual RPCPPE;


b.	The Accounting Office and the Inventory Committee reconcile the PPE balances in the RPCPPE, PPE schedules5, and the FS, and the Municipal Accountant present the correct balances in the FS;

c.	The Accounting Office provide complete and correct details of the current and future PPE acquisitions for reference in the computation of depreciation; and



d.	Thereafter, ensure that depreciation is provided once the asset is available for use.

We recommended and Management agreed to:

The Accounting Office and the Inventory Committee reconcile the PPE balances between the RPCPPE and the FS, and the Municipal Accountant present the correct balances in the FS;


The Management effect the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts in accordance with the guidelines and procedures prescribed under COA Circular No. 2020-006.

We recommended and the management agreed that:
The Inventory Committee prepare and submit the CY 2023 RPCPPE immediately, and henceforth ensure the timely preparation and submission of the annual RPCPPE;
The Accounting Office and the Inventory Committee reconcile the PPE balances in the RPCPPE, PPE schedules, and the FS, and the Municipal Accountant present the correct balances in the FS;
The Accounting Office provide complete and correct details of the current and future PPE acquisitions for reference in the computation of depreciation; and
Thereafter, ensure that depreciation is provided once the asset is available for use.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
Pending submission of liquidation report, the Municipal Accountant shall not debit to eliminate the trust liability account from the books;
Determine the status of liquidations of unsettled fund transfers reflected in the books of the Province that has been fully liquidated in the books of the Municipality, and if necessary, provide the Provincial Accountant copies of liquidation documents that have been submitted so that the unrecorded settlement will be taken up in the books of the Province;
Cause the reconciliation of the inter-agency payable account Due to LGUs of the Municipality with that of the reciprocal receivable account Due from LGUs of the Province, and effect the necessary adjusting entries on the variance noted to reflect the correct balances of said accounts; and
Conduct a periodic reconciliation of inter-agency reciprocal accounts to ensure accurate balances of payable/receivable accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended and the Municipal Accountant agreed to:
Verify/check the amounts in liquidation reports submitted to the Provincial Accountant of fund transfers with discrepancies in the balance recorded in the books of the Province;
Determine the status of liquidations of unsettled fund transfers reflected in the books of the Province that has been fully liquidated in the books of the Municipality, and if necessary, provide the Provincial Accountant of copies of liquidation documents that have been submitted so that the unrecorded settlement will be taken up in the books of the Province;
Cause the reconciliation of the inter-agency payable account Due to LGUs of the Municipality with that of the reciprocal receivable account Due from LGUs of the Province, and effect the necessary adjusting entries on the variance noted to reflect the correct balances of said accounts; and
Conduct a periodic reconciliation of inter-agency reciprocal accounts to ensure accurate balances of payable/receivable accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended and the Municipal Accountant agreed to: 

regularly provide the Provincial Accountant with data on the Province’s share in the real property and other tax collections made by the Municipality;

remit the valid current due Province’s share in real property and other taxes which remained unremitted by the Municipality;

validate the documents for the Transfer, Ante Mortem, Post Mortem and Professional Taxes due the Province to facilitate the immediate remittance thereof; and

verify receipt of liquidation documents already submitted to the Province and submit liquidation documents for other fund transfers recorded by the Province as receivable from the Municipality.

We recommended and the Municipal Accountant agreed to:

record the fund transfers for the implementation of programs and projects as Due to LGUs to set up the receivable account;

send written demand for liquidation reports from the Barangay for the financial assistance granted;

ensure that fund transfers for the implementation of programs and projects be supported with pertinent documents required in COA Circular No. 2012-001; and

require liquidation reports from the LGUs concerned before granting additional fund transfers.

We recommended and Management agreed to:

require the concerned implementing offices to expedite the completion of the on-going development projects, namely: 1) Construction of Multi-purpose building, 2) Development of potential water sources, 3) Infrastructure projects to schools and barangays, and 4) Acquisition of lot for informal settlers;

direct the Municipal Development Council to ensure that the development projects identified in the ADP are feasible and can be implemented within the year with the proposed budget allocation;

require the implementation of the development projects within the time schedule as targeted in the ADP and optimally utilize the 20% Development Fund.

We recommended and Management agreed that:

the Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction Management Council (MDRRMC) through the DRRM Designate Officer ensure that the PPAs in the MDRRM Plan are aligned with those of the national council’s pre-disaster preparedness programs and activities and that the 70% allocation of the MDRRMF are utilized only for such authorized PPAs;


the DRRM Designate Officer:
ensure that the programs, projects and activities in the MDRRM Plan are in line with the strategies and objectives set for disaster preparedness, mitigation and prevention;

ensure that the planned DRRM PPAs are fully implemented within the target implementation period; and

the Municipal Accountant make sure that all payment transactions are supported with complete documentation.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:

the Local Finance Committee allocate 1% of the IRA for the strengthening and implementation of programs, projects and   activities for the protection of children;

the MCPC articulate properly the PPAs in the LDIP with primary focus on child friendly programs, projects and services;

provide identical information on PPAs and their budget allocations in the LDIP and Accomplishment Report to allow proper evaluation and assessment of outputs against the plans; 

the MCPC measure the results of implemented PPAs against the LDIP and submit a report thereon to the concerned Offices including COA Audit Team for proper evaluation.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
for PPEs under Land, Land Improvements, Power Supply System and Buildings and Other Structures, the Head of the Inventory Committee determine from the accounting records the period of recorded transactions by going through prior years’ records and noting actual period of occurrence;

the Inventory Committee and the Municipal Accountant retrieve relevant records to determine corresponding transactions in (a);

a physical inventory-taking of PPE items under Land, Land Improvements, Power Supply System and Buildings and Other Structures classifications be conducted on the results of (a) and (b);

subsequently, corresponding adjustments shall be made in both the property and accounting records; and,

for items which were not recorded in the accounting records, a Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) be drawn to adjust the account balances in the books of accounts, if warranted, in order to reflect accurate amounts in the financial statements.

We recommended and the Municipal Accountant agreed to:
send written demand for liquidation reports from the Provincial Government, barangays and Liga ng mga Barangay for the financial assistance granted;

ensure that fund transfers for the implementation of programs and projects be supported with Memorandum of Agreement and other pertinent documents required in COA Circular No. 2012-001; 

henceforth, record fund transfers for the implementation of programs and projects as Due to LGUs to set up the receivables account; and,

require liquidation reports from the LGUs concerned before granting additional fund transfers.

We recommended and the Municipal Accountant agreed to: 
regularly provide the Provincial Accountant with data on the Province’s share in the real property and other tax collections made by the Municipality;

remit the valid current due Province’s share in real property and other taxes which remained unremitted by the Municipality;

trace the details of the fund transfers by requesting copies of Journal Entry Vouchers (JEVs) of the Province;

submit liquidation documents for fund transfers recorded by the Province as Due from LGUs; and,

conduct periodic reconciliation with the Provincial Accountant.

We recommended and the Municipal Development Council through the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator agreed to:

see to it that the utilization of the 20% DF be optimally utilized;

conduct a close monitoring and evaluation of the implementation of the 20% development programs and projects as provided in Section 109.5 of R.A. No. 7160 so that early detection of deficiencies/ problems/shortfalls may be rectified within the project duration;

develop feasible solutions to address the identified problems such as the identification of water source to implement the Water Supply and Sanitation System Project and the revision/modification of target beneficiaries as requirement in the implementation of the Solar Power Electrification Project; and,

coordinate with other agencies such as the DPWH to avoid inclusion of programmed development projects which are not feasible to implement.

